2. TreeMap <String, Integer>
Comparator: (a,b) -> a.length() - b.length(). This means sorting by length.

java
treeMap.merge("dd", 4, Integer::sum);
No key "dd" → put("dd", 4).

treeMap.merge("fff", 6, Integer::sum); → put("fff", 6).

treeMap.put("c", 3); → length 1.

treeMap.put("aa", 1); → length 2.

treeMap.put("bb", 2); → length 2.

treeMap.merge("e", 5, Integer::sum); → put("e", 5) (length 1).

TreeMap sorted by length. For ties, insertion order? No — TreeMap with comparator doesn’t keep order within same length for duplicates — but since we compare by length only, keys of same length are equal by comparator, so only one can exist? Wait! Wrong! Keys with same length compare equal, so later ones overwrite earlier.

But compare only returns 0 when lengths equal, so "aa" and "bb" are equal by comparator, so "aa" first then "bb" replaces "aa". Similarly "c" and "e" length 1 → "c" then "e" replaces "c".

Thus final:

Length 1 keys: "e"
Length 2 keys: "bb"
Length 3 keys: "fff" and "dd" are equal length 3 → "fff" inserted first, then "dd" replaces "fff".

So final: {e=5, bb=2, dd=4}.

3. LinkedHashMap <Integer, String> with access-order and LRU
java
LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> linkedMap = new LinkedHashMap<>(16, 0.75f, true) {
    @Override
    protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry<Integer,String> eldest) {
        return size() > 3;
    }
};
Initial:
linkedMap.put(4, "D") → {4=D}
linkedMap.put(3, "C") → {4=D, 3=C}
linkedMap.get(2) → null, no change.
linkedMap.get(1) → null, no change.

linkedMap.put(1, "A") → {4=D, 3=C, 1=A} (size 3)
linkedMap.put(2, "B") → size 4 → eldest 4 removed → {3=C, 1=A, 2=B}

linkedMap.put(5, "E") → size 4 → eldest 3 removed → {1=A, 2=B, 5=E}

Final: {1=A, 2=B, 5=E}.

4. IdentityHashMap <Integer, String>
Key Integer but uses reference equality.

java
Integer a = 127, b = 127, c = 128, d = 128;
b and a are same object? No — Integers from -128 to 127 are cached, so a==b true for 127. For 128, new objects each time.

identityMap.put(b, "Y") → b=127
identityMap.put(a, "X") → a=127 same as b, so this replaces "Y" with "X".

identityMap.put(c, "Z") → c=128 new object
identityMap.put(d, "W") → d=128 new object, so not equal to c, separate entry.

Final map: {127="X", 128="Z", 128="W"} but print order? IdentityHashMap iterates over internal array order. Likely 127, 128, 128 in order of insertion.

